'''SMS ''G113''''' was an {{sclass-|S90|torpedo boat}} built for the German ''[[Kaiserliche Marine]]'' (Imperial Navy) in the 1900s

==Design==
{{main article|S90-class torpedo boat}}
''G113'' was {{convert|65.8|m|ftin}} [[overall length|long overall]] and {{convert|65.5|m|ftin}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]], with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|6.7|m|ftin}} and a [[Draft (ship)|draught]] of {{convert|2.87|m|ftin}}. [[Displacement (ship)|Displacement]] was {{convert|330|t|LT}} normal and {{convert|440|t|LT}} full load.<ref name="Grob2 p43">Gröner 1983, p. 43.</ref> Three coal-fired [[water-tube boiler]]s fed steam to 2 sets of [[Compound steam engine#Multiple expansion engines|Triple expansion steam engine]]s rated at {{convert|6013|PS|ihp kW}}, giving a speed of {{convert|29|kn}}.<ref name="Grob2 p43"/><ref name="conways60 p264">Chesneau and Kolesnik 1979, p. 264.</ref> {{convert|112|t|LT}} of coal was carried, giving a range of {{convert|1225|nmi}} at {{convert|17|kn}}.<ref name="Grob2 p43"/>

Armament consisted of three [[5 cm SK L/40 gun]]s in single mounts, together with three {{convert|450|mm|in|1}} torpedo tubes,<ref name="conways60 p265">Chesneau and Kolesnik 1979, p. 265.</ref> with two spare torpedoes.<ref name="Grob2 p43"/> The ship was later re-armed, with an 8.8 cm gun replacing one of the 5.0 cm guns.<ref name="Grob2 p43"/>

==Service history==
''G113'' was launched at [[Friedrich Krupp Germaniawerft|Germaniawerft]]'s [[Kiel]] shipyard on 9 August 1902, and commissioned on 16 October 1902.<ref name="Grob2 p44">Gröner 1983, p. 44.</ref> In May 1907, she was a member of the 1st Half Flotilla.<ref>''Rangeliste der Kaiserlisch-Deutschen Marine für das Jahr 1907 '' p. 29.</ref> She was renamed ''T113'' on 4 September 1914.<ref name="Grob2 p44">Gröner 1983, p. 44.</ref> In April 1915, ''T113'' was a member of the 7th Torpedo-boat Half Flotilla, operating in the [[Baltic sea]].<ref>Firle 1929, p. 46.</ref>

